<h2>A Consumer&rsquo;s Guide to Fair Trade: Defining the Movement and Benefits</h2>

						<p>Fair Trade is a form of alternative trade culture that has existed in modern form since 1946. It is an anti-poverty movement that bases its actions on the motto of “trade, not aid”. The concept of Fair Trade is based on the belief that economic justice can be achieved by creating an economy based on eco-friendliness, fair prices, humane work conditions, and sustainable manufacturing practices. To be called Fair Trade, products and producers have to be certified by one of a number of Fair Trade certification organizations. Products that are Fair Trade certified bear Fair Trade certification logos on their packaging.</p>

						<p><b><br/></b></p>

						<h3><b>Definition & Structure of the Fair Trade Movement</b></h3>

						<p>The Fair Trade movement is dedicated toward helping consumers and producers of goods participate in a system of trade that is in the best interest of those involved. They do this by ensuring that farm workers, jewelry-makers, and those who make other non-food items, enjoy a healthy work environment. To this end, the movement also seeks to enforce proscriptions against child labor and all forms of slavery. Fair Trade also strives to achieve fair prices for goods by means of a price floor, in order to support decent wages for the workers who make the goods. These price floors are also designed to support technological and infrastructure development to improve the workers' standard of living. Farmers must also work cooperatively, in a democratic environment where the workers have a say in the way the business is run.</p>

						<p>To make certain that these principles are adhered to, Fair Trade certification organizations visit farmers and producers of goods to audit them. They establish the proper price floors and ensure that goods are being sold at those prices. In addition, they look at working conditions, the pay that the workers receive, the money invested in improvements, and other factors, before deciding whether to renew or grant the organization their Free Trade certification. Many organizations also audit the environmental aspect of production, by measuring the ecological impact of the making of food or goods in question.</p>

						<p>Organic certification is a concept that pertains to the impact of farming methods on the environment. Farmers that are organic certified do not use synthetic pesticides or other harmful chemicals. Organic certification doesn't address the issue of supply chains, work environments, child labor, or wages. Fair Trade, however, has evolved to encompass both fair trade and eco-friendly principles. The World Trade Federation, for instance, lists protecting the environment as one of its “Ten Principles of Fair Trade.” Fair Trade certified producers are often encouraged to become organic certified as well. Almost half of all farmers who are certified as Fair Trade are also officially certified as organic farmers.</p>
