						<h3><b>Product Certification</b></h3>

						<p>The process of certifying a product as Fair Trade starts at the beginning of the supply chain. A certification organization such as FLO-CERT will visit the farm in question, or premises where crafted goods are made, and audit the working conditions there. They also verify that there is no discrimination, child labor or slavery involved in the production process. Then they will look at the wages paid to the workers, and the prices charged by the farmers, to ensure that they obey the price floor set by the certifying organization. This price floor includes a ten percent price premium that is intended to support the business. Some organizations like TransFair USA will also check to make sure that agricultural chemicals are not overused. Eco-Social/IBD is an organization that only certifies agricultural products that are worthy of both Fair Trade and organic certification. Each certification organization has its own label that it grants producers and their goods.</p>
